<TITLE> UK Labour support up despite plot vs Brown: poll </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Support for Britain's ruling Labour party has firmed slightly over the past month despite a failed attempt to oust Prime Minister Gordon Brown this week, according to an opinion poll in the Sunday Telegraph. The survey by ICM found support for Labour was one point higher than a month ago at 30 percent. The Conservatives were steady at 40 percent and the Liberal Democrats down one point at 18 percent. The ICM poll, conducted on Jan. 6-7, showed more voters thought Labour would do better without Brown as leader than worse, but the margin -- 41 percent versus 35 percent -- was relatively small. By contrast a YouGov poll in the Sun newspaper on Friday suggested 67 percent of voters either had no confidence in the ruling Labour Party or less confidence following Wednesday's unsuccessful putsch. Two former cabinet ministers called for a secret ballot of Labour parliamentarians to decide if Brown should lead the party into an election due within the next five months. The call, which Brown called a "storm in a tea cup", failed to win any high-level support but the episode renewed questions about the prime minister's authority. If repeated at an election, the ICM poll would give the Conservatives a parliamentary majority of just 16 seats. Markets are concerned the election could produce a hung parliament or a government so weak it would not be able to take the tough measures needed to cut Britain's record budget defi
